    <section id="trends">
      <h2>Trends to watch</h2>

      <h3>1. The Unity MCP ecosystem is real</h3>
      <p>
        Two Unity-focused MCP servers now sit in the top 4: CoplayDev/unity-mcp (#1) and CoderGamester/mcp-unity (#4).
        Both score above 96, driven by strong freshness, active issue management, and growing contributor counts.
        Game engine integration is an underrated use case for MCP &mdash; Unity's scripting model maps
        cleanly to tool-call patterns, and agent-controlled game objects are compelling for both dev tooling
        and automated testing.
      </p>

      <h3>2. Enterprise tooling entering the top tier</h3>
      <p>
        microsoft/azure-devops-mcp reached #2 this week with a 32-point score jump. Enterprise tools
        historically lag in the index because they score lower on the "dependents" signal (fewer repos
        depend on them vs. SDK-style tools). This jump suggests the freshness and issue health signals
        are carrying it &mdash; likely reflecting active development at Microsoft. If Azure DevOps MCP
        goes GA, it could stay in the top 5 on volume of usage signals alone.
      </p>

      <h3>3. Most of the index is stale</h3>
      <p>
        65.3% of indexed repositories (16,746 out of 25,638) have no commit activity in the last 60 days.
        This is the silent majority of the MCP ecosystem: experimental repos, tutorials, weekend projects,
        and abandoned forks. The AgentRank scoring model penalizes this heavily via the freshness signal
        (25% of total score). Only 150 tools currently score above 80.
      </p>

      <h3>4. Microsoft now holds two spots in the top 10</h3>
      <p>
        microsoft/playwright-mcp entered the top 10 this week at #10 (94.23 score, 29,150 stars) &mdash; joining
        microsoft/azure-devops-mcp at #2. With 29K stars, playwright-mcp is the most-starred repo in the top 10
        by a wide margin. It's a web automation server that gives AI agents full Playwright browser control
        through MCP. The score reflects its freshness, issue activity, and enormous dependent footprint.
        Two Microsoft tools in the top 10 is a new development for this index.
      </p>

      <h3>5. AI agent infrastructure is emerging as a category</h3>
      <p>
        This week's new entries included a security scanner for agents (agent-shield), a fleet memory system
        (memclawz), a production agent framework (mayros), and ComfyUI workflow bridges. These are tools
        that operate one layer above standard MCP servers &mdash; they use MCP as transport but solve
        higher-level agent coordination problems. Watch for this category to grow fast in Q2.
      </p>
    </section>

